revision.text:
In zoological nomenclature, '''emendations''' are alterations made to the spelling of [[taxon]] names. In bacteriological nomenclature, emendations are made to the [[Circumscription (taxonomy)|circumscription]] of a taxon.<ref>{{citation |editors=Lapage, S.; Sneath, P.; Lessel, E.; Skerman, V.; Seeliger, H.; Clark, W. |year=1992 |title=International Code of Nomenclature of Bacteria: Bacteriological Code, 1990 Revision |publisher=ASM Press |location=Washington (DC) |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK8808/}} '''Rule 35'''</ref>
==In zoology== The change must be consciously made along with justification for altering the spelling originally used by the taxon author while describing the species. Any other spelling changes are considered to be unjustified. Valid emendations include changes made to correct:<ref>{{cite journal|title =Emendation of Zoological Names| author=Follett, W.I|journal=Systematic Biology|year=1952|volume= 1 |issue=4|pages=178-181|doi=10.1093/sysbio/1.4.178}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Article 32 of the ICZN|url=http://www.nhm.ac.uk/hosted-sites/iczn/code/?article=32|publisher=ICZN}}</ref> * typographical errors in the original work describing the species * errors in transliteration from non-Latin languages * names that included diacritics, hyphens * endings of species to match the gender of the generic name, particularly when the combination has been changed The binomial authority remains unchanged.
